  | issue = 5
  | pages = 1599<U+2013>609
  | pmc = 1378010
  | postscript = .
| doi=10.1086/302902
}}
</ref><ref name=discov>{{cite web
| title = First Americans Endured 20,000-Year Layover <U+2013> Jennifer Viegas, Discovery News
| url =http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american.html
| accessdate = 2009-11-18
|quote=Archaeological evidence, in fact, recognizes that people started to leave Beringia for the New World around 40,000 years ago, but rapid expansion into North America didn't occur until about 15,000 years ago, when the ice had literally broken
| postscript = .}} [http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american-02.html page 2]</ref> Around 16,500 years ago, the [[Last Glacial Maximum|glaciers began melting]], allowing people to move south and east into Canada and beyond.<ref name="aaa">{{cite journal
  | last = Tamm
  | first = Erika
  | coauthors = et al
