The first inhabitants entered the Americas pursuing [[Pleistocene]] mammals such as the [[Giant Beaver|giant beaver]], [[steppe wisent]], [[musk ox]], [[mastodons]], [[woolly mammoth]]s and  ancient reindeer (early caribou).<ref name="Gibbard">{{cite book
  | last = Gibbard
  | first = P
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors = van Kolfschoten, T.
  | title = A Geologic Time Scale
|chapter=The Pleistocene and Holocene Epochs
  | work = Gowin Institute for Quaternary Research
  | publisher = Quaternary Palaeoenvironments Group, Department of Geography, University of Cambridge
|location=[[Cambridge University Press]], UK
  | year = 2004
|isbn=0521781426
  | url = http://www-qpg.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/gibbard/GTS2004Quat.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-18
  | unused_data = chapter 22 }}</ref>  One route hypothesized is that people walked south by way of an ice-free corridor on the east side of the [[Rocky Mountains]], and then fanned out across North America before continuing on to South America.<ref name="albert">{{cite book |url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=dZYGdbWTXesC&lpg=PA6&dq=paleo%20indians%20fanned%20out%20across%20North%20America%20before%20continuing%20on%20to%20South%20America&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=true|title=American environmental history: an introduction |first=Carolyn |last=Merchant|publisher=Columbia Univ. Press |year=2007|isbn=9780231140348|page=6 | accessdate = 2011-01-26}}</ref>  The other conjectured route is that they migrated, either on foot or using [[boat#History|primitive boats]], down the [[Pacific Coast]] to the tip of South America, and then crossed the Rockies and [[Andes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeology.about.com/gi/o.htm?zi=1/XJ&zTi=1&sdn=archaeology&cdn=education&tm=25&f=00&tt=13&bt=1&bts=1&zu=http%3A//www.jstor.org/stable/279189|title=Alternate Migration Corridors for Early Man in North America|work=American Antiquity, Vol. 44, No. 1 (Jan., 1979), p2 | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref> Evidence of the latter has been covered by a [[sea level rise]] of hundreds of metres following the last ice age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclimate.org/index.php/archives/2009/01/sea-will-rise-to-levels-of-last-ice-age/|title=68 Responses to Sea will rise <U+2018>to levels of last Ice Age|work=Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite book
  | last = Harris
  | first = A.G.
  | coauthors = E. Tuttle, S.D. Tuttle,
  | title = Geology of National Parks
|edition=5
  | publisher =  Kendall/Hunt Publishing
|isbn=0-7872-5353-7
|location=Iowa
  | year = 1997
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=Xr7v7GNmHs0C&dq=Geology+of+National+Parks&printsec=frontcover&q=
  | format = 6th edition is online by Google Books
  | accessdate = 2009-10-18}}</ref>

The Old Crow Flats and basin was one of the areas in Canada untouched by glaciations during the [[Quaternary glaciation|Pleistocene Ice ages]], thus it served as a pathway and refuge for ice age plants and animals.<ref name="mountain">{{cite web
  | title = Life in Crow Flats-Part 1
  | work = Old Crow's official Website
  | publisher = Vuntut Gwitchin First Nation
  | date = 1998<U+2013>2009
  | url = http://www.oldcrow.ca/cf1.htm
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}</ref> The area holds evidence of early human habitation in Canada dating from about 20,000 years ago and ending about [[9th millennium BC|11,000 years ago]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction |work=Government of Canada|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/eng/docs/r/pfa-fap/sec1.aspx|year=2009|accessdate=2010-01-09|quote=Canada's oldest known home is a cave in Yukon occupied not 12,000 years ago like the U.S. sites, but at least 20,000 years ago}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pleistocene Archaeology of the Old Crow Flats|publisher=Vuntut National Park of Canada|url=http://yukon.taiga.net/vuntutrda/archaeol/info.htm |year=2008|accessdate=2010-01-10|quote=However, despite the lack of this conclusive and widespread evidence, there are suggestions of human occupation in the northern Yukon about 24,000 years ago, and hints of the presence of humans in the Old Crow Basin as far back as about 40,000 years ago.}}</ref> Fossils from the area include some never accounted for in North America, such as [[hyena]]s and large [[camel]]s.<ref name="taiga.net">{{cite web|url=http://www.taiga.net/wetlands/oldcrow/oc_gen.html|title=Old Crow Flats|publisher=taiga.net|accessdate=2007-08-05}}</ref> Bluefish Caves is an archaeological site in the [[Yukon|Yukon Territory]] of Canada from which a specimen of apparently human-worked mammoth bone has been radiocarbon dated to 18,000 years ago.<ref name=Griebel>{{cite web
  | last = Griebel
  | first = Ron
  | title = The Bluefish Caves
  | publisher = Minnesota State University
  | date =
  | url = http://www.mnsu.edu/emuseum/archaeology/sites/northamerica/bluefishcaves.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Beringia: humans were here
  | work = Gazette (Montreal)
  | publisher = CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc.
  | date = May 17, 2008
  | url = http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/saturdayextra/story.html?id=2a31375e-e834-407d-b8db-2a0010ad4acf&p=2
  | format = re-published online by Canada.com
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref>

During the 1950s, geologists first conjectured that an ice-free corridor ran north and south through Alberta during the [[Last glacial period|Late Wisconsin period]].<ref name="albert"/><ref>{{cite book
|last=Wilson
|first=M. C.
|coauthors=J. A. Burns
|editor=R. Bonnichsen and K. L. Turnmire
|title=Ice Age People of North America: Environments, Origins and Adaptations
|year=1999
|publisher=Oregon State University Press and Center for the Study of the First Americans
|location=Corvallis, Oregon
|page=213
|chapter=Searching for the earliest Canadians: wide corridors, narrow doorways, small windows
|isbn=9780870714580
}}
</ref> [[Lithic reduction]] stone scrapers and choppers were preserved from archaeological sites in [[Bow River|Grimshaw, Bow River]], and [[Lethbridge]].<ref name="albert">{{cite book
|last=Dickason
|first=Olive
|title=Canada's First Nations: A History of the Founding Peoples from the Earliest Times
|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]
|location=Toronto
|isbn=0-19-541358-X
}}
</ref> These  [[Lithic flake]]d  stone tools discovered under glacial sand and gravel are classified as pre-glacial and indicate nomadic humans occupied the area as early as 23,000 years ago.<ref name="albert"/> Archaeologists are still finalising the dates recorded for the Alberta and the Old Crow flats sites.<ref>{{cite book
  | last =  Gibbon
  | first = Guy E.
  | coauthors = Kenneth M. Ames
  | title = Archaeology of prehistoric native America: an encyclopedia
|year=1998
  | publisher = Taylor & Francis.
|format=Re-published online by Google books
  | page = 682
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=_0u2y_SVnmoC&pg=RA1-PA682&lpg=RA1-PA682&dq=old+crow+caves+debate&q=old%20crow%20caves%20debate
| accessdate = 2009-10-06
  | isbn =  9780815307259}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chlachula and
  | first = Jiri
  | coauthors =  Louise Leslie
  | title = Preglacial archaeological evidence at Grimshaw, the Peace River area, Alberta: Reply1
  | work = NRC Canada
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | year = 2001
  | url = http://pubs.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/rp/rppdf/e01-030.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}
</ref>
[[Image:Clovis Point.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt="A Clovis  blade with medium to large lanceolate spear-knife points. Side is parallel to convex and exhibit careful pressure flaking along the blade edge. The broadest area is near the midsection or toward the base. The Base is distinctly concave with a characteristic flute or channel flake removed from one or, more commonly, both surfaces of the blade.  The lower edges of the blade and base is ground to dull edges for hafting. Clovis points also tend to be thicker than the typically thin latter stage  Folsom points. Length: 4<U+2013>20 cm/1.5<U+2013>8 in. Width: 2.5<U+2013>5 cm/1<U+2013>2 | A [[Clovis point]] created using [[Lithic reduction|bi-facial percussion flaking]].<br>(that is, each face is flaked on both edges alternatively with a percussor) <U+2013> Image courtesy of the Virginia Dept. of Historic Resources.]]
Clovis sites dated at 13,500 years ago were discovered in western North America during the 1930s. [[Clovis culture|Clovis peoples]] were regarded as the first widespread [[Paleo-Indians|Paleo-Indian]] inhabitants of the [[New World]] and ancestors to all indigenous peoples in the Americas.<ref name="cloves">{{cite book |title=Ice Age People of North America |last=Lepper |first=Bradley T. |authorlink= |editor=Bonnichsen, Robson; Turnmire, Karen |year=1999 |publisher=Oregon State University Press |location=Corvallis |isbn=9780870714 |pages=362<U+2013>394 |chapter=Pleistocene Peoples of Midcontinental North America }}</ref> Archaeological discoveries in the past thirty years have brought forward other distinctive [[knapping]] cultures who occupied the Americas from the lower [[Great Plains]] to the shores of [[Chile]].<ref name="Firestone2007">{{ cite journal | last = Firestone | first = R. B. | authorlink = | coauthors = et al. | year = 2007 | month = | title = Evidence for an extraterrestrial impact 12,900 years ago that contributed to the megafaunal extinctions and the Younger Dryas cooling | journal = [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]] | volume = 104 | issue = 41 | pages = 16016<U+2013>16021 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0706977104 | url = | accessdate =2009-09-18 | pmid = 17901202 |isbn=0870714589 | pmc = 1994902 }}</ref>

Localised regional cultures developed from the time of the [[Younger Dryas]] cold climate period from 12,900 to 11,500 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kennett DJ, Kennett JP, West A, et al. |title=Nanodiamonds in the younger dryas boundary sediment layer |journal=Science (journal) |volume=323 |issue=5910 |page=94 |year=2009 |month=January |pmid=19119227 |doi=10.1126/science.1162819 |url=|accessdate=2009-10-06 |postscript=. }}</ref> The [[Folsom tradition]]  are characterised by their use of [[Folsom point]]s as projectile tips at archaeological sites.  These tools assisted activities at kill sites that marked the slaughter and butchering of bison.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Hillerman
|first= Anthony G.
|title=The Great Taos Bank Robbery and Other Indian Country Affairs.
|year=1978
|publisher=[[University of New Mexico]] press
|isbn=0-8263-0306-4
|chapter=The Hunt for the Lost American}}
</ref>

The land bridge existed until 13,000{{emdash}}11,000 years ago, long after the oldest proven human settlements in the New World began.<ref name=mapSurvey>{{cite web |url=http://www.erudit.org/revue/GPQ/1988/v42/n1/032714ar.pdf |format=PDF |work=Dyke A.S. & Prest V.K |title=Late Wisconsinian and Holocene retreat of the Larentide ice sheet. vol. 42, n<U+00B0> 1, 1988, p. 101<U+2013>102 |publisher= [[Geological Survey of Canada]] | accessdate =2009-10-17}}</ref> Lower sea levels in the [[Queen Charlotte Sound (Canada)|Queen Charlotte sound]] and [[Hecate Strait]] produced great grass lands called ''archipelago of Haida Gwaii''.<ref name="hadi">{{cite web
  | title =  Prehistory of Haida Gwaii
  | work = Civilization.ca-Haida-The people and the land-Prehistory
|publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization Corporation
  | date = June 8, 2001
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/aborig/haida/happr01e.shtml
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}</ref>
[[Hunter-gatherer]]s of the area left distinctive [[lithic technology]] tools and the remains of large butchered mammals, occupying the area from 13,000{{emdash}}[[7th millennium BC|9,000 years ago]].<ref name="hadi"/> In July 1992, the Federal Government officially designated [[X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem]] as a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site]], one of the first Indigenous spiritual sites in Canada to be formally recognised in this manner.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem: A cultural, historic and spiritual First Nations site--X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem Longhouse Interpretive Centre, Mission, BC, Canada
  | publisher = X<U+0332><U+00E1>:ytem Longhouse Interpretive Centre,
  | date = 2003<U+2013>2009
  | url = http://www.xaytem.ca/archives.php
  | accessdate = 2009-09-18}}
</ref>

The Plano culture was a group of hunter-gatherer communities that occupied the Great Plains area of North America between 12,000{{mdash}}10,000 years ago.<ref name="palo">{{cite web
  | last =  Reynolds
  | first = Graham
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors = Richard MacKinnon, Ken MacDonald and Folkus Atlantic Productions
  | title = Period 1 (10,000{{emdash}}8,000 years ago) Palaeo-Indian culture
  | work =  Learners Portal
  | url = http://www.learnersportal.com/CanadaFP/Ancient/per1.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> The Paleo-Indians moved into new territory as it emerged from under the glaciers.  Big game flourished in this new environment.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Early North American Cultures
  | work = MSU EMuseum
  | publisher = Minnesota State University
  | year = 2007
  | url = http://www.mnsu.edu/emuseum/prehistory/northamerica/culture/index.html
  | accessdate =2009-09-18 }}
</ref> The Plano culture are characterised by a range of projectile point tools collectively called [[Plano point]]s, which were used to hunt [[bison]].  Their diets also included [[pronghorn antelope]], [[elk]], [[deer]], [[raccoon]] and [[coyote]].<ref name="palo"/> At the beginning of the [[Archaic period in the Americas|Archaic Era]], they began to adopt a [[Sedentary lifestyle|sedentary]] approach to subsistence.<ref name="palo"/> Sites in and around [[Belmont, Nova Scotia]] have evidence of Plano-Indians, indicating small seasonal hunting camps, perhaps re-visited over generations from around 11,000{{emdash}}10,000 years ago.<ref name="palo"/> Seasonal large and smaller game fish and fowl were food and raw material sources. Adaptation to the harsh environment included tailored clothing and skin-covered tents on wooden frames.<ref name="palo"/>
{{Clear}}

===Archaic period===
{{See also|Pre-Columbian era}}
The North American climate stabilized by 8000&nbsp;[[Common Era|BCE]]
(10,000 years ago); climatic conditions were very similar to today's.<ref name="icaage">{{cite book
|last=Imbrie
|first=J
|coauthors= K.P.Imbrie
|title=Ice Ages: Solving the Mystery
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|year=1979
|page=135
|publisher=Enslow Publishers
|location=Short Hills NJ
|url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=GIxRp9fRDGwC&lpg=PP1&dq=Ice%20Ages%3A%20Solving%20the%20Mystery&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true
|isbn=0226668118
}}
</ref> This led to widespread migration, [[Plant cultivation|cultivation]] and later a dramatic rise in population all over the Americas.<ref name="icaage"/> Over the course of thousands of years, American indigenous peoples domesticated, bred and cultivated a large array of plant species. These species now constitute 50 <U+2013> 60% of all crops in cultivation worldwide.<ref>{{cite book
|last=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service
|title=Foreign agriculture
|volume=24
|year=1962
|publisher= Bureau of Agricultural Economics
|location=United States
|page=167
|isbn=016038463X
}}
</ref>
[[File:Na-Dene langs.png|thumb|right|alt="Map of North America showing in red the pre-contact distribution of Na-Dene languages"|Distribution of [[Na-Dene languages]] shown in red]]
The vastness and variety of Canada's climates, [[ecology]], [[vegetation]], [[fauna]], and landform separations have defined ancient peoples implicitly into cultural or [[Linguistics|linguistic]] divisions. Canada is surrounded north, east, and west with coastline and since the last ice age, Canada has consisted of distinct forest regions. Language contributes to the identity of a people by influencing social life ways and spiritual practices.<ref name="prepre"/> Aboriginal religions developed from [[anthropomorphism]] and [[animism]] philosophies.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Friesen
|first=John
|title=Rediscovering the [[List of First Nations peoples|First Nations of Canada]].
|year=1997
|publisher=Detselig Enterprises Ltd
|location=Calgary, AB
|isbn=1550591436
}}
</ref>

The placement of artifacts and materials within an Archaic burial site indicated social differentiation based upon status.<ref name="icaage"/> There is a continuous record of occupation of [[St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D>|S'<U+00F3>lh T<U+00E9>m<U+00E9>xw]] by Aboriginal people dating from the early [[Holocene]] period, 10,000{{emdash}}9,000 years ago.<ref name="thor">{{cite book
|title=You Are Asked to Witness: The St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D> in Canada's Pacific Coast History
|year=1997
|publisher= St<U+00F3>:l<U+014D> Heritage Trust
|location=Chilliwack, BC
|isbn= 0-9681577-0-X
|editor2=Carlson, Keith Thor
}}
</ref> Archaeological sites at [[Stave Lake]], [[Coquitlam Lake]], [[Fort Langley, British Columbia|Fort Langley]] and region uncovered early period artifacts. These early inhabitants were highly mobile hunter-gatherers, consisting of about 20 to 50 members of an extended family.<ref name="thor"/><ref>{{cite web |author=Jacobs, James Q. |year=2002 |title=Paleoamerican Origins by James Q. Jacobs |work=Paleoamerican Origins: A Review of Hypotheses and Evidence Relating to the Origins of the First Americans |url=http://www.jqjacobs.net/anthro/paleoamerican_origins.html |work=Anthropology and Archaeology Pages |publisher=jqjacobs.net|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> The [[Na-Dene languages|Na-Dene]] people occupied much of the land area of northwest and central North America starting around 8,000&nbsp;BCE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyandtheheadlines.abc-clio.com/ContentPages/ContentPage.aspx?entryId=1171754&currentSection=1161468&productid=5|title=American Indian Heritage Month: Commemoration vs. Exploitation|work=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> They were the earliest ancestors of the [[Athabaskan languages|Athabaskan]]-speaking peoples, including the [[Navajo people|Navajo]] and [[Apache]]. They had villages with large multi-family dwellings, used seasonally during the summer, from which they hunted, fished and gathered food supplies for the winter.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Leer
|first=Jeff
|coauthors= Doug Hitch, & John Ritter
|title=Interior [[Tlingit noun]] dictionary: The dialects spoken by Tlingit elders of Carcross and [[Teslin, Yukon]], and [[Atlin, British Columbia]]
|year=2001
|publisher=Yukon Native Language Centre
|location=[[Whitehorse, Yukon]] Territory
|isbn=1-55242-227-5
}}
</ref> The [[Wyandot people|Wendat]] peoples settled into [[Southern Ontario]] along the [[Eramosa River]] around 8,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;BCE (10,000{{emdash}}9,000&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="ray"/> They were concentrated between [[Lake Simcoe]] and [[Georgian Bay]]. Wendat hunted caribou to survive on the glacier-covered land.<ref name="ray">{{cite book
|last=Ray
|first= Arthur J.
|title=I Have Lived Here Since The World Began: An Illustrated [[History of Canada]]'s Native People
|year=1996
|publisher= Lester Publishing
|location=Toronto, ON
|isbn=155263633X
}}</ref> Many different First Nations cultures relied upon the buffalo starting by 6,000{{emdash}}5,000&nbsp;BCE (8,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="ray"/> They hunted buffalo by herding migrating buffalo off cliffs. [[Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump]], near [[Lethbridge, Alberta]], is a hunting grounds that was in use for about 5,000 years.<ref name="ray"/>
[[Image:Cambridge Bay Thule Site 1998-06-28.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Photograph of a circular arrangement of rocks on open ground with a body of water in the background|[[Thule people|Thule]] site ([[Copper Inuit]]) near the waters of Cambridge Bay ([[Victoria Island (Canada)|Victoria Island]]) ]]
The west coast of Canada by 7,000{{emdash}}5000&nbsp;BCE (9,000{{emdash}}7,000&nbsp;years ago) saw various cultures who organised themselves around salmon fishing.<ref name="ray"/> The [[Nuu-chah-nulth people|Nuu-chah-nulth]] of [[Vancouver Island]] began whaling with advanced long spears at about this time.<ref name="ray"/> The [[Maritime Archaic]] is one group of North America's [[Archaic stage|Archaic]] culture of sea-mammal hunters in the [[subarctic]]. They prospered from approximately 7,000&nbsp;BCE{{emdash}}1,500&nbsp;BCE (9,000{{emdash}}3,500 years ago) along the [[Arctic Ocean|Atlantic Coast]] of North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therooms.ca/museum/mnotes12.asp|title=
Museum Notes-The Maritime Archaic Tradition|work=By James A. Tuck-The Rooms Provincial Art Gallery|accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref> Their settlements included [[longhouses]] and boat-topped temporary or seasonal houses. They engaged in long-distance trade, using as currency white [[chert]], a rock quarried from northern Labrador to Maine.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Tuck
|first=J. A.
|title=The excavation of an Archaic Indian Cemetery in Newfoundland. Newfoundland Social and Economic Studies 17
|year=1976
|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research
|location=St. John's
|chapter=Ancient peoples of Port au Choix
|isbn=0919666124
}}
</ref> The [[Pre-Columbian]] culture, whose members were called [[Red Paint People]], is indigenous to the [[New England]] and [[Atlantic Canada]] regions of North America. The culture flourished between 3,000&nbsp;BCE{{emdash}}1,000&nbsp;BCE (5,000{{emdash}}3,000&nbsp;years ago) and was named after their burial ceremonies, which used large quantities of red [[ochre]] to cover bodies and grave goods.<ref>{{cite web
|title=The so-called "Red Paint People
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|year=1997
|publisher=University of Maine
|work=Brian Robinson
|url=http://www.seacoastnh.com/history/prehistoric/redpaint.html
}}</ref>

The [[Arctic small tool tradition]] is a broad cultural entity that developed along the [[Alaska Peninsula]], around [[Bristol Bay]], and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait around [[25th century BC|2,500&nbsp;BCE]] (4,500&nbsp;years ago).<ref name="Fagan">{{cite book
|last=Fagan
|first=Brian M.
|title=Ancient North America: The Archaeology of a Continent.
|edition=4
|year=2005
|publisher=Thames & Hudson Inc.
|location=New York
|pages=390, p396
|isbn=0500281483
}}
</ref> These [[Paleo-Arctic Tradition|Paleo-Arctic]] peoples had a highly distinctive toolkit of small blades ([[Microblade technology|microblades]]) that were pointed at both ends and used as side- or end-barbs on [[arrows]] or spears made of other materials, such as bone or [[antler]]. [[Scraper (archaeology)|Scrapers]], engraving tools and [[adze]] blades were also included in their toolkits.<ref name="Fagan"/> The Arctic small tool tradition branches off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset, and the [[Independence II culture|Independence traditions]]. These two groups, ancestors of [[Thule people]], were displaced by the Inuit by 1000&nbsp;[[Common Era]] (CE).<ref name="Fagan"/>{{rp|179<U+2013>81}}
{{Clear}}

===Post-Archaic periods===
{{See also|List of archaeological periods (North America)}}
{{Annotated image | float=right
| image=Hopewellsphere2 map HRoe 2008.jpg
| width=200
| imageleft=-150
|height=100
| caption=Great Lakes area of the [[Hopewell tradition|Hopewell Interaction Area]] <br />PP{{=}}[[Point Peninsula Complex]]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;S=[[Saugeen Complex]]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;L=[[Laurel Complex]]
|image-width=200
| alt=A northerly section focusing on the Saugeen, Laurel and Point Peninsula complexes of the map showing south eastern United States and the Great Lakes area of Canada showing the Hopewell Interaction Sphere and in different colours the various local expressions of the Hopewell cultures, including the Laurel Complex, Saugeen Complex, Point Peninsula Complex, Marksville culture, Copena culture, Kansas City Hopewell, Swift Creek Culture, Goodall Focus, Crab Orchard culture and Havana Hopewell culture.
|float = right
|annotations=
{{Annotation|148|28|'''PP'''}}
{{Annotation|130|45|'''S'''}}
{{Annotation|115|10|'''L'''}}
}}
The [[Old Copper Complex]] societies dating from 3,000&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}500&nbsp;BCE (5,000{{emdash}}2,500&nbsp;years ago) are a manifestation of the [[Woodland period|Woodland Culture]], and are pre-pottery in nature.<ref name="Winchell">{{cite book
|last=Winchell
|first=N.H.
|title=Ancient Copper Mines of Isle Royale,
|volume=19
|year=1881
|publisher=[[Popular Science]] Monthly
|location=New York
|pages=601<U+2013>2
}}
</ref> Evidence found in the northern [[Great Lakes]] regions indicates that they  extracted [[copper]] from local glacial deposits and used it in its natural form to manufacture tools and implements.<ref name="Winchell"/>

The Woodland cultural period dates from about 2,000&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}1,000&nbsp;CE, and has locales in Ontario, Quebec, and Maritime regions.<ref>{{cite web
|title=C. Prehistoric Periods (Eras of Adaptation)
|publisher=The University of Calgary (The Applied History Research Group)
|year=2000
|url=http://www.ucalgary.ca/applied_history/tutor/firstnations/periods.html
| accessdate = 2010-04-15}}</ref> The introduction of pottery distinguishes the Woodland culture from the earlier Archaic stage inhabitants. [[Laurentides|Laurentian]] people of southern Ontario manufactured the oldest pottery excavated to date in Canada.<ref name="prepre"/> They created pointed-bottom beakers decorated by a cord marking technique that involved impressing tooth implements into wet clay. Woodland technology included items such as beaver incisor knives, bangles, and chisels.  The population practicing sedentary agricultural life ways continued to increase on a diet of squash, corn, and bean crops.<ref name="prepre">{{cite book
|last=Fagan
|first=Brian M
|others=University of California
|title=People of the Earth: An Introduction to World Prehistory
|year=1992
|publisher=[[HarperCollins|Harper Collins]]
|isbn=032101457X
}}
</ref>

The Hopewell tradition is an Aboriginal culture that flourished along American rivers from 300&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}500&nbsp;CE. At its greatest extent, the [[Hopewell Exchange System]] networked [[culture]]s and societies with the peoples on the Canadian shores of [[Lake Ontario]]. Canadian expression of the Hopewellian peoples encompasses the [[Point Peninsula Complex|Point Peninsula]], [[Saugeen Complex|Saugeen]], and [[Laurel Complex|Laurel complexes]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = A History of the Native People of Canada
  | work = Dr. James V. Wright
  | publisher = [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]]
  | year = 2009
  | url = http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/archeo/hnpc/npvol25e.shtml
  | accessdate = 2009-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Ohio Historical Society |url =http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=1283 | title = Hopewell Culture-Ohio History Central-A product of the Ohio Historical Society|publisher=Hopewell-Ohio History Central|year=2009|accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref><ref name="Price">{{cite book | author= Douglas T. Price, and Gary M. Feinman | year= 2008 | title= Images of the Past, 5th edition | pages= 274<U+2013>277 | location= New York | publisher=McGraw-Hill | isbn= 978-0 07-3405209 }}</ref>

====First Nations ====
{{Main|First Nations}}
[[File:Chief George and daughter.jpg|thumb|left|alt="Black and white photograph of Skwxwu7mesh Chief George from the village of Senakw with his daughter in traditional regalia."|Chief George from the village of [[Senakw]] with his daughter in traditional [[regalia]], c.1906]]
First Nations peoples had settled and established trade routes across what is now Canada by 500&nbsp;BCE{{mdash}}1,000&nbsp;CE. Communities developed each with its own culture, customs, and character.<ref name="Joe">{{cite book
|last=Joe
|first=Rita
|coauthors=Lesley Choyce
|title=The Native Canadian Anthology
|year= 2005
|publisher=Nimbus Publishing (CN)
|isbn= 1-895900-04-2
}}
</ref>  In the northwest were the [[Athapaskan]], [[Slavey people|Slavey]], [[Dogrib]], [[Tutchone]], and  [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]].  Along the Pacific coast were the [[Tsimshian]];[[Haida people|Haida]]; [[Coast Salish peoples|Salish]]; [[Kwakiutl]]; [[Nuu-chah-nulth people|Nootka]]; [[Nisga'a]]; [[Senakw]] and [[Gitxsan]]. In the plains were the [[Blackfoot]]; [[Kainai Nation|K<U+00E1><U+00ED>nawa]]; [[Sarcee]] and [[Blackfoot|Peigan]]. In the northern woodlands were the [[Cree]] and [[Chipewyan]]. Around the Great Lakes were the [[Anishinaabe]]; [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]]; [[M<U+00ED>kmaq]]; [[Iroquois]] and [[Wyandot people|Huron]]. Along the Atlantic coast were the [[Beothuk]], [[Maliseet]], [[Innu]], [[Abenaki people|Abenaki]] and [[Mi'kmaq people|Mi'kmaq]].

Many Canadian Aboriginal [[civilization|civilisations]] established characteristics and hallmarks that included permanent or urban settlements, [[agriculture]], civic and [[Mound builder (people)|monumental architecture]], and [[complex society|complex societal hierarchies]].<ref name="Complex ">{{Cite book
  | author = [[Peter Turchin]], [[Leonid Grinin]], [[Andrey Korotayev]], and Victor C. de Munck.Turchin
  | title = History and mathematics: Historical Dynamics and Development of Complex Societies
|format=URSS.ru-Books on Science-On-line Bookstore.
  | url = http://edurss.ru/cgi-bin/db.pl?lang=en&blang=en&page=Book&id=53185
|editor= Moscow: KomKniga/[[Editorial URSS|URSS]], 2006. |isbn=5484010020 |accessdate=2009-10-18
  | postscript = .
}}</ref> These civilisations had evolved and changed by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th<U+2013>early 16th centuries), and have been brought forward through archaeological investigations.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Willey
|first=Gordon R
|authorlink=
|coauthors=Philip Phillips
|title=Method and Theory in American Archaeology
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|year=1957
|publisher= University of Chicago Press
|isbn=978-0-226-89888-9
|pages=1(introduction)
|first1= |last3=
|url=http://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=6136197
}}
</ref>

There are indications of contact made before [[Christopher Columbus]] between the first peoples and those from other continents.  Aboriginal people in Canada interacted with Europeans around 1000 CE, but prolonged contact came after Europeans established permanent settlements in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name="Woodcock, part I">{{cite book
|author=[[George Woodcock]]
|title=A Social History of Canada
|date=January 25, 1990
|publisher=Penguin Books Ltd
|isbn=0140105360,978-0140105360
|chapter=Part 1
}}
</ref> In Columbus' time there was speculation that other Europeans had made the trip in ancient or contemporary times; [[Gonzalo Fern<U+00E1>ndez de Oviedo y Vald<U+00E9>s]] records in his ''General y natural historia de las Indias'' of 1526, which includes biographical information on Columbus.<ref name="Madrid">{{cite book
|last= de Amez<U+00FA>a
|first=Agust<U+00ED>n G.
|title=Introduction to the facsimile reprint of ''Libro de Claribalte''
|year=1956
|publisher=  [[Spanish Royal Academy]]Madrid
|location=Madrid
}}
</ref>  European written accounts generally recorded friendliness of the First Nations, who profited in trade with Europeans.<ref name="Woodcock, part I"/>  Such trade generally strengthened the more organised political entities such as the [[Iroquois Confederation]].<ref>{{cite book
|author=[[Eric Wolf]]
|title=[[Europe and the People Without History]]
|accessdate=2009-10-06
|date=December 3, 1982
|publisher=University of California Press; 1 edition
|isbn= 0520048989, 978-0520048980
|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/40564/Eric-Wolf-Europe-and-the-People-Without-History-introduction
|chapter=Chapter 6
}} URL gives introduction online</ref> Throughout the 16th century, European fleets made almost annual visits to the eastern shores of Canada to cultivate the fishing opportunities. A sideline industry emerged in the un-organised [[Fur trade|traffic of furs]] overseen by the [[Indian Department]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/?id=oHlLvzRZ-1sC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=fur+trade+and+the++Indian+Department&q=fur%20trade%20and%20the%20%20Indian%20Department |title=A Narrow Vision: Duncan Campbell Scott and the Administration of Indian |work=By E. Brian Titley|format=Re-published online by Google books |location=Vancouver |publisher=University Of British Columbia Press|year= 1992|isbn= 0774804203|accessdate=2009-10-15}}</ref>

Prominent First Nations people include Joe Capilano, who met with King of the United Kingdom, [[Edward VII]], to speak of the need to settle [[land claims]] and [[Ovide Mercredi]], a leader at both the [[Meech Lake Accord]] constitutional reform discussions and [[Oka Crisis]].<ref>{{cite news
  | title = Ovide Mercredi installed as chancellor of Manitoba's newest university
  | publisher = CBC News
  | date = November 7, 2007
  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/canada/manitoba/story/2007/11/07/mercredi-chancellor.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = The History of Metropolitan Vancouver's Hall of Fame Joe Capilano
  | url = http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/whoswho_C.htm
  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}
</ref>

====Inuit====
{{Main|Inuit}}
The Inuit are the descendants of what [[Anthropology|anthropologists]] call the Thule culture, which emerged from western Alaska around 1,000&nbsp;CE and spread eastward across the [[Arctic]], displacing the [[Dorset culture]] (in [[Inuktitut]], the Tuniit). Inuit historically referred to the Tuniit as "giants", or "dwarfs", who were taller and stronger than the Inuit.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Rigby
  | first = Bruce
  | title = 101. Qaummaarviit Historic Park, Nunavut Handbook
  | url = http://www.nunavuthandbook.com/parks_pgs_297_331.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Wood
  | first = Shannon Raye
  | title = Tooth Wear and the Sexual Division of Labour in an Inuit Population
  | work = Department of Archaeology University of Saskatchewan
  | publisher = Simon Fraser University
  | date = April 1992
  | url = http://ir.lib.sfu.ca/bitstream/1892/5348/1/b14258730.pdf
  | format =PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> Researchers hypothesize that the Dorset culture lacked dogs, larger weapons and other technologies used by the expanding Inuit society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historysociety.ca/content/en/pdfs/Jamieson2.pdf|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071030193732/http://www.historysociety.ca/content/en/pdfs/Jamieson2.pdf|archivedate=2007-10-30|title=The Dorsets: Depicting Culture Through Soapstone Carving|format=PDF  | accessdate =2009-10-05}}</ref> By 1300, the Inuit had settled in west [[Greenland]], and finally moved into east Greenland over the following century. The Inuit had trade routes with more southern cultures. Boundary disputes were common and led to aggressive actions.<ref name=warin>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/aboriginal/innu_culture.html|title=Innu Culture 3. Innu-Inuit 'Warfare'|work=1999, Adrian Tanner
Department of Anthropology-Memorial University of Newfoundland| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>
[[File:Inuit hunter with harpoon.jpg|thumb|alt="black and white image of an [Inuit hunter seated in a kayak holding a harpoon"|[[Inuit|Inuk]] in a [[kayak]], c. 1908<U+2013>1914]]
[[War]]fare was common among Inuit groups with sufficient population density. Inuit, such as the [[Nunatamiut]] ([[Uummarmiut]]) who inhabited the [[Mackenzie River]] delta area, often engaged in common warfare.  The Central Arctic Inuit lacked the population density to engage in warfare. In the 13th century, the Thule culture began arriving in Greenland from what is now Canada. Norse accounts are scant. Norse-made items from Inuit campsites in Greenland were obtained by either trade or plunder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/aboriginal/inuit_history.html|title=Inuit Post-Contact History|work=Memorial University of Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada.| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref> One account, [[:is:<U+00CD>var B<U+00E1>r<U+00F0>arson|<U+00CD>var B<U+00E1>r<U+00F0>arson]], speaks of "small people" with whom the Norsemen fought.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Hans Christian Gull<U+00F8>v
|title=Gr<U+00F8>nlands Forhistorie
|year=2005
|isbn=87-02-017245-5
|page=17}}
</ref> 14th-century accounts that a western settlement, one of the two Norse settlements, was taken over by the [[Skr<U+00E6>ling]].<ref>{{cite book
|last= Fitzhugh
|first=William W.
|editor=Fitzhugh, William W. and Elisabeth I. Ward,
|title=Vikings: The [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]] Saga
|year=2000
|publisher= [[Smithsonian Institution]]
|location=Washington, D.C.
|isbn= 15-60-98995-5
|pages=193<U+2013>205
}}
</ref>

After the disappearance of the Norse colonies in Greenland, the Inuit had no contact with Europeans for at least a century. By the mid-16th century, [[Basque people|Basque]] fishers were already working the Labrador coast and had established whaling stations on land, such as been excavated at [[Red Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador|Red Bay]].<ref>{{cite book
  | last =McGhee
  | first = Robert
  | title =  Northern Approaches. Before Columbus: Early European Visitors to the New World
  | publisher = The Beaver.Exploring Canada's History
  | date =June/July 1992
|volume=3
  | page = 194
|isbn=12-18-094632-4
}}</ref>  The Inuit appear not to have interfered with their operations, but they did raid the stations in winter for tools, and particularly worked iron, which they adapted to native needs.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Kleivan
  | first = H
  | title = The Eskimos of Northeast Labrador
  | publisher = Norsk Polarinstitutt
Skrifter
  | year = 1966
|volume = 139
|page=9
|isbn=17-66-78922-6}}
</ref>

Notable among the Inuit are [[Abraham Ulrikab]] and family who became a [[zoo]] exhibit in [[Hamburg]], Germany, and [[Tanya Tagaq]], a traditional [[Inuit throat singing|throat singer]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Minogue
  | first = Sarah
  | title = When Inuit become zoo curiosities "We sat there like pieces of art in a showcase on display"
  | date = September 23, 2005
  | url = http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/50923/news/features/50923_01.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-06 }}
</ref> [[Abe Okpik]], [[Order of Canada|CM]], was instrumental in helping Inuit obtain [[Family name|surnames]] rather than [[disc numbers]] and [[Kiviaq (person)|Kiviaq]] (David Ward) won the legal right to use his single-word Inuktituk name.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Kiviaq versus Canada film by Zacharias Kunuk Produced by Katarina Soukup
  | publisher = Isuma Distribution International Inc.
  | year = 2006
  | url =http://www.canadacouncil.ca/NR/rdonlyres/97B12343-AC79-4ED6-AC1E-055350618B16/0/InuitFactSheetEN.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =  Hanson
  | first = Ann Meekitjuk
  | title = Nunavut 99-What's In A Name? Names, as well as events, mark the road to Nunavut
  | publisher = Nunavut.com
  | date =
  | url = http://www.nunavut.com/nunavut99/english/name.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref>

====M<U+00E9>tis====
{{Main|M<U+00E9>tis people (Canada)}}
[[File:Mixed blood Fur trader 1870.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Black and white photograph of a man with a short moustache and earings, wearing a fur lined dress jacket, bow tie and fur hat|upright|[[Mixed-blood|Mixed blood]] [[North American fur trade|fur trader]], c.1870]]
The M<U+00E9>tis are a people descended from marriages between Europeans (mainly French<ref>{{cite book
|last=Rinella
|first=Steven
|title=American Buffalo: In Search of A Lost Icon
|accessdate=2009-10-18
|year=2008
|publisher=Spiegel and Grau
|location=NY
|isbn=0385521685
|page=166
|url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=Qc3laE5ymFcC&lpg=PP1&dq=American%20Buffalo%3A%20In%20Search%20of%20A%20Lost%20Icon&pg=PA166#v=onepage&q&f=true
}}
</ref>) and Cree, Ojibway, Algonquin, [[Saulteaux]], [[Menominee]], Mi'kmaq, [[Maliseet]], and other First Nations.<ref name=testt>{{cite web
  | title = What to Search: Topics-Canadian Genealogy Centre-Library and Archives Canada
  | work = Ethno-Cultural and Aboriginal Groups
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 2009-05-27
  | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/genealogie/022-905.004-e.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> Their history dates to the mid-17th century.<ref name="First Nations Culture Areas Index"/>
The M<U+00E9>tis homeland consists of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian provinces]] of [[British Columbia]], [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Manitoba]], [[Quebec]], [[New Brunswick]], [[Nova Scotia]], and [[Ontario]], as well as the [[Northwest Territories]] (NWT).<ref>{{cite book
|last=Howard
|first=James H
|title=The Plains-Ojibwa or Bungi: hunters and warriors of the Northern Prairies with special reference to the Turtle Mountain band
|edition=Museum Anthropology Papers 1
|year=1965
|publisher= [[University of South Dakota]]
|isbn=0160504007
}}
</ref>

Amongst notable M<U+00E9>tis people are [[Tom Jackson (actor)|Tom Jackson]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/manitoba/story/2009/10/23/mb-tom-jackson-dreamcatcher-housing.html |title=Singer Tom Jackson pitches housing complex for Winnipeg |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2009-10-23 |accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> [[TV|television]] actor, [[Tony Whitford]], [[Commissioner of the Northwest Territories]], and Louis Riel who led two resistance movements: the [[Red River Rebellion]] of 1869<U+2013>1870 and the [[North-West Rebellion]] of 1885, which ended in his [[Trial of Louis Riel|trial]].<ref name="LouisRielCE">{{cite web
 | last =The Canadian Encyclopedia
 | first =Historica Foundation of Canada.
 | title =Riel, Louis
 | year =2007
 | url =http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0006837
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | publisher =A database of materials held by the University of Saskatchewan Libraries and the University Archives
 | title =Louis Riel
 | url =http://library2.usask.ca/northwest/background/riel.htm
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Brown
  | first = Jane
  | title = Aboriginal Faces of Saskatchewan <U+2013> Tom Jackson
  | work = Saskatchewan Sage <U+2013> April 1998 <U+2013> pg. 6
  | publisher = Saskatchewan Indian Cultural Centre
  | date =
  | url = http://www.sicc.sk.ca/faces/mjackto.htm
  | accessdate =2009-10-05 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Backgrounder  Biography of Anthony W.J. (Tony) Whitford <U+2013> NWT Commissioner
  | work = Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | publisher = 2005 News Releases
  | date = 2008-10-28
  | url = http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ai/mr/nr/j-a2005/02623bk-eng.asp
  | accessdate =2009-10-06 }}
</ref><ref name="martyr">{{cite web
 | last = Ricketts
 | first =Bruce
 | title =Louis Riel <U+2013> Martyr, hero or traitor?
 | year =1998<U+2013>2007
 | url =http://www.mysteriesofcanada.com/Canada/riel.htm
 | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}</ref>

The languages inherently M<U+00E9>tis are either [[M<U+00E9>tis French]] or a mixed language called [[Michif language|Michif]]. Michif, Mechif or M<U+00E9>tchif is a [[Pronunciation spelling|phonetic spelling]] of M<U+00E9>tif, a variant of M<U+00E9>tis.<ref name=mist>{{cite web|url=http://metisresourcecentre.mb.ca/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72&Itemid=13|title=The Problem of Michif|work=By Peter Bakker-Metis Resource Centre (ISBN 0{{emdash}}19<U+2013>509711<U+2013>4)| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref> The M<U+00E9>tis today predominantly speak [[Canadian English|English]], with [[Canadian French|French]] a strong second language, as well as numerous [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|Aboriginal tongues]]. A 19th-century community of the M<U+00E9>tis people, the [[Anglo-M<U+00E9>tis]], were referred to as Countryborn.  They were children of [[Rupert's Land]] fur trade typically of [[Orcadian]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], or English paternal descent and Aboriginal maternal descent.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Barkwell
|first=Lawrence J.
|coauthors=Leah Dorion, and Audreen Hourie
|title=Metis legacy Michif culture, heritage, and folkways
|volume=Metis legacy series, v. 2.
|year=2006
|publisher= [[Gabriel Dumont Institute]],
|location=Saskatoon, SK
|isbn=0920915809
}}
</ref>  Their first languages would have been Aboriginal ([[Cree language|Cree]], [[Saulteaux language|Saulteaux]], [[Assiniboine language|Assiniboine]], etc.) and English.  Their fathers spoke [[Canadian Gaelic|Gaelic]], thus leading to the development of an English dialect referred to as "[[Bungee language|Bungee]]".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Red River dialect|work=Blain,  Eleanor M. (1994)|publisher= Winnipeg: Wuerz Publishing|url=http://tceplus.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0001097 | accessdate =2009-10-15 }}</ref>

There is debate over legally defining the term M<U+00E9>tis.<ref name=legal>{{cite web|url=http://www.metisnation.ca/who/definition.html|title=National Definition of M<U+00E9>tis |work=M<U+00E9>tis National Council| accessdate =2009-10-15 }}</ref>  Unlike First Nations people and Inuit, there is no distinction between [[Indian Register|status]] and non-status.<ref name=legal/>  S.35 of the Constitution Act, 1982 mentions the M<U+00E9>tis.  M<U+00E9>tis, their heritage and aboriginal ancestry have been absorbed and assimilated into their surrounding populations.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Barkwell
|first= Lawrence J.
|coauthors= Leah Dorion and Darren Prefontaine
|title=Metis Legacy: A Historiography and Annotated Bibliography
|year= 2001
|publisher= Pemmican Publications Inc. and Saskatoon: Gabriel Dumont Institute
|location=Winnipeg, MB
|isbn=1-894717-03-1
}}
</ref> On September 23, 2003, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] ruled that M<U+00E9>tis are a distinct people with significant rights ([[Powley ruling]]).<ref name=pow>{{cite web
|url=http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/2003/2003scc43/2003scc43.pdf
|format=PDF
|title=Her Majesty The Queen vs. Steve Powley and Roddy Charles Powley (R. v. Powley, 2 S.C.R. 207, 2003 SCC 43)
|publisher=Federation of Law Societies of Canada
|year=2003
|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref>

===Integration ===
[[File:Stpauls-middlechurch-man.jpg|thumb|upright|right|St. Paul's Indian Industrial School, Middlechurch, Manitoba, 1901]]
{{Main|Canadian Indian residential school system|Indian Residential Schools Truth and Reconciliation Commission}}
From the late 18th century, European Canadians encouraged Aboriginals to assimilate into their own culture, referred to as "[[Culture of Canada|Canadian culture]]".<ref name = "RoyalCom-sg3">{{cite web | title = Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | work = Stage Three: Displacement and Assimilation
  | publisher = Government of Canada Web Archive-websites archived by Library and Archives Canada.
  | date =  2006-02-08
  | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/webarchives/20071124124236/http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ch/rcap/sg/sgm6_e.html
  | accessdate = 2009-10-03}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Report-Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples-Indian and Northern Affairs Canada
  | work = Volume 1, Part 1, Chapter 6 of the ''Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples''
  | publisher = Government of Canada Web Archive-websites archived by Library and Archives Canada [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]]
  | date = 2006-02-08
  | url =http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/webarchives/20071115053257/http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ch/rcap/sg/sgmm_e.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-03 }}
</ref>  These attempts reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries with forced integration. Because of laws and policies that encouraged or required Aboriginals to [[Cultural imperialism|assimilate]] into a [[Eurocentrism|Eurocentric]] society, Canada may be violating the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide|Genocide Convention]] that Canada signed in 1949 and passed through Parliament in 1952.<ref name="Restoule, Jean-Paul 2002">{{cite book
|last=Restoule
|first=Jean-Paul
|title=Aboriginal Identity: The Need for Historical and Contextual Perspectives
|accessdate=2009-10-28
|year=2002
|publisher=Pearson/Prentice Hall
|location=Toronto, ON
|pages=252 261
|url=http://eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/detail?accno=EJ630059
|chapter= Seeing Ourselves. John Macionis and Nijole v. Benokraitis and Bruce Ravelli
}}
</ref> The residential school system that removed Aboriginal children from their homes for placement in Christian-run schools has led scholars to believe that Canada can be tried in [[international court]] for [[genocide]].<ref name="Restoule, Jean-Paul 2002" />  In 2008 [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] issued an apology on behalf of the Canadian government and its citizens for the residential school system.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Benjoe
  | first = Kerry
  | title = Group gathers for Harper's apology
  | publisher =  The Leader-Post
  | date =  June 12, 2008
  | url = http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/story.html?id=2e362bf9-0f5a-43c6-ab5e-81a276b4767c
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref>

==Politics, law and legislation==
{{main|The Canadian Crown and Aboriginal peoples}}

===Treaties===
{{See|Numbered Treaties}}
[[Image:Medal-Viki.jpg|250px|thumb|left|alt=Photograph showing the two sides of a round silver medal, showing the profile of Queen Victoria on one side and the inscription "Victoria Regina", with the other side having a depiction of a man in European garb shaking hands with an Aboriginal in historic first nation clothing with the inscription "Indian Treaty 187"|The Indian Chiefs Medal, presented to commemorate [[Numbered Treaties|Treaties]] [[Treaty 3|3]], [[Treaty 4|4]], [[Treaty 5|5]], [[Treaty 6|6]] and [[Treaty 7|7]], bearing the image of [[Queen Victoria]].]]
[[The Canadian Crown and Aboriginal peoples]] began [[Timeline of colonization of North America|interactions]] during the European colonialisation period.  [[Numbered treaties]], the  [[Indian Act]], the  [[Constitution Act, 1982|Constitution Act of 1982]] and case laws were established. Aboriginals construe these agreements as being between them and the [[Monarchy of Canada|Crown of Canada]] through the [[Indian Agent (Canada)|districts Indian Agent]], and not the [[Cabinet of Canada]].<ref name=FN>{{Cite document| last=Assembly of First Nations| author-link=Assembly of First Nations| last2=Elizabeth II| author2-link=Elizabeth II| contribution=A First Nations <U+2013> Federal Crown Political Accord| contribution-url = http://firstpeoplesofcanada.com/fp_treaties/john_fp33_indianact.html| series=1| year=2004| page=3| place=Ottawa| publisher=Assembly of First Nations| url=http://firstpeoplesofcanada.com/fp_treaties/john_fp33_indianact.html| accessdate=2009-11-17| postscript=.}}</ref>
The [[M<U+0101>ori people|M<U+0101>ori]] interprets the [[Treaty of Waitangi]] in New Zealand similarly.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =  Mainville
  | first = Sara
  | title = Lawsuits, treaty rights and the sacred balance
  | publisher = Toronto Star
  | date = June 1, 2007
  | url = http://www.thestar.com/comment/article/220171
  | accessdate =2009-10-02}}
</ref> A series of eleven [[treaty|treaties]] were signed between Aboriginals in Canada and the reigning Monarch of Canada from 1871 to 1921.  The [[Government of Canada]] created the policy, commissioned the Treaty Commissioners and ratified the agreements.  These Treaties are agreements with the Government of Canada administered by [[Canadian Aboriginal law]] and overseen by the [[Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development (Canada)|Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Treaty areas
  | work = Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat
  | publisher = Government of Canada
  | date = 2002-10-07
  | url = http://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/dfrp-rbif/treaty-traite.asp?Language=EN
  | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070822043231/http://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/dfrp-rbif/treaty-traite.asp?Language=EN
  | archivedate = 2007-08-22
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref>

According to the ''First Nations<U+2013> Federal Crown Political Accord'' "cooperation will be a cornerstone for partnership between Canada and First Nations, wherein ''Canada'' is the short-form reference to Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Canada.<ref name=FN /> The [[Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court]] argued that treaties "served to reconcile pre-existing Aboriginal sovereignty with assumed Crown sovereignty, and to define Aboriginal rights".<ref name=FN>{{cite web
  | title = A First Nations-Federal Crown Political Accord on the Recognition and Implementation of First Nation Governments
  | work = Assembly of First Nations & Government of Canada
  | date = April 19, 2004
  | url = http://firstpeoplesofcanada.com/fp_treaties/john_fp33_indianact.html
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref> First Nations people interpreted agreements covered in [[treaty 8]] to last "as long as the sun shines, grass grows and rivers flow."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/aboriginals/treaty8.html|title=What is Treaty 8?|work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation| accessdate =2009-10-05 }}</ref>
{{Clear}}

===Indian Act and Bill C-31===
{{Main|Indian Act}}
[[File:Crombie1983.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of former Federal Minister for Indian Affairs and Northern Development, the Honourable David Crombie speaking to reporters on the floor of the 1983 Progressive Conservative leadership convention|Former Federal Minister for Indian Affairs and Northern Development, the Honorable [[David Crombie]] was responsible for Bill C-31<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Wuttunee
  | first = Deanna
  | title = Indian Act Amendments <U+2013> Bill C-31
|work=Saskatchewan Indian
  | publisher = Saskatchewan Indian Cultural Centre
  | date = July 1985
  | url = http://www.sicc.sk.ca/saskindian/a85jul13.htm
|quote="Recognizing the right of Indian communities and bands to determine their own members marks a historic departure from a century of paternalism. It is also a milestone in the Government's desire to advance towards greater recognition of Indian self-government."
| accessdate = 2009-10-19}}
</ref> ]]
The Indian Act is federal legislation that dates from 1876. There have been over twenty major changes made to the original Act since then, the last time being in 1951; amended in 1985 with [[Bill C-31]]. The Indian Act indicates how Reserves and Bands can operate and defines who is recognised as an "Indian".<ref name="laws">{{cite web
  | title = Update notice to the Justice Laws site
  | work = Indian Act. R.S., 1985, c. I-5
  | publisher = Department of Justice Canada
  | date = 2009-09-29
  | url = http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/laws/stat/rsc-1985-c-i-5/31743/rsc-1985-c-i-5.html#history
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref>

In 1985, the Canadian Parliament passed Bill C-31, "An Act to Amend the Indian Act". Because of a Constitutional requirement, the Bill took effect as of April 17, 1985.<ref name="bill">{{cite web
  | title = First Nations, Bill C-31, Indian Act
  | work = Communications Branch
  | publisher = Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development
  | url = http://www.johnco.com/nativel/bill_c31.html
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>
* It ends discriminatory provisions of the Indian Act, especially those that discriminated against women.<ref name="bill"/>
* It changes the meaning of "status" and for the first time allows for limited reinstatement of Indians who were denied or lost status and/or Band membership.<ref name="bill"/>
* It allows bands to define their own membership rules.<ref name="bill"/>

Those people accepted into band membership under band rules may not be status Indians. C-31 clarified that various sections of the Indian Act would apply to band members. The sections under debate concern community life and land holdings. Sections pertaining to Indians (Aboriginals) as individuals (in this case, wills and taxation of personal property) were not included.<ref name="bill"/>
{{Clear}}

===Royal Commission ===
{{Main|Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples}}

The [[Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples]] was a  [[Royal Commission]] undertaken by the Government of Canada in 1991 to address issues of the Aboriginal peoples of Canada.<ref name=royal/> It assessed past government policies toward Aboriginal people, such as [[Canadian Indian residential school system|residential schools]], and provided policy recommendations to the government.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = The Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples
  | work =  Mary C. Hurley, Law and Government Division, Jill Wherrett, Political and Social Affairs Division
  | publisher = Government of Canada (Library of Canada)
  | date = 4 October 1999
  | url =http://www.parl.gc.ca/information/library/PRBpubs/prb9924-e.htm
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}
</ref> The Commission issued its final report in November 1996. The five-volume, 4,000{{emdash}}page report covered a vast range of issues; its 440 recommendations called for sweeping changes to the interaction between Aboriginal, non-Aboriginal people and the governments in Canada.<ref name=royal>{{cite web|url=http://www.iog.ca/publications/healthrcap.pdf|format=PDF |title=Summary of the Final Report of The Royal Commission on Aboriginal |work=CTV Canada| accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> The report "set out a 20{{emdash}}year agenda for change."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/information/library/PRBpubs/prb9924-e.htm|title=the Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples|work= Library of Parliament | accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref>

===Health policy===
{{Main|Indian Health Transfer Policy (Canada)}}
In 1995, the [[Government of Canada|federal government]] announced the Aboriginal Right to Self-Government Policy.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = I- Aboriginal Health &amp; Cultural Diversity Glossary, College of Nursing
  | publisher = [[University of Saskatchewan]]
  | year = 2003
  | url = http://www.usask.ca/nursing/aboriginalglossary/i.htm
  | accessdate = 2009-10-02}}
</ref> This policy recognises that First Nations and Inuit have the constitutional right to shape their own forms of government to suit their particular historical, cultural, political and economic circumstances. The [[Indian Health Transfer Policy (Canada)|Indian Health Transfer Policy]] provided a framework for the assumption of control of health services by Aboriginal peoples, and set forth a developmental approach to transfer centred on self-determination in health.<ref>{{cite book
  | last =Jacklin
  | first =Kristen
  | coauthors = Wayne Warry
  |editor=Arachu Castro, Merrill Singer
  | title = Unhealthy health policy: a critical anthropological examination
  |chapter=14 Then Indian Health Transfer Policy in Canada: Toward Self-Determination or Cost Containment?
  |format=digitised online by Google books
  | publisher = Rowman Altamira
  |place=Oxford United Kingdom
  | year = 2004
  | page = 215
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=XWbF_tfYUuEC&pg=PA215&lpg=PA215&dq=Indian+Health+Transfer+Policy+in+canadal&q=
  | isbn =0-7591-0510-3
| accessdate =2009-10-06}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Indian Health Policy 1979
  | work = About Health Canada > Branches & Agencies > First Nations & Inuit Health Branch
  | publisher = Health Canada
  | date = 2007-10-25
  | url = http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/branch-dirgen/fnihb-dgspni/poli_1979-eng.php
  | format = php
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>  Through this process, the decision to enter transfer discussions with [[Health Canada]] rests with each community. Once involved in transfer, communities can take control of health programme responsibilities at a pace determined by their individual circumstances and health management capabilities.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Lemchuk-Favel
  | first = Laurel
  | title = Financing a First Nations and Inuit Integrated Health System A Discussion Document
  | work = Heallth Canada
  | publisher =
  | date = February 22, 1999
  | url = http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/fniah-spnia/alt_formats/fnihb-dgspni/pdf/pubs/agree-accord/1999_finance_integr-eng.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}
</ref>  The [[National Aboriginal Health Organization]] (NAHO) incorporated in 2000, is an Aboriginal-designed and-controlled not-for-profit body in Canada that works to influence and advance the health and well-being of Aboriginal Peoples.<ref name="naho">{{cite web |url=http://www.naho.ca/english/|title=National Aboriginal Health Organization (NAHO) |work= Conference Board creates northern research centre|accessdate=2009-10-14}}</ref>

===Political organization===
{{Main|First Nations government (Canada)|M<U+00E9>tis National Council|Inuit Circumpolar Council}}
First Nations and Inuit organisations ranged in size from [[Band society|band societies]] of a few people to multi-nation confederacies like the Iroquois. First Nations leaders from across the country formed the [[Assembly of First Nations]], which began as the National Indian Brotherhood in 1968.<ref name="price">{{cite book |last=Price |first=Richard |title=The Spirit of the Alberta Indian Treaties|publisher=University of Alberta Press > the University of Michigan |year=1999|isbn=0888643276}}</ref>

Today's political organisations have resulted from interaction with European-style methods of government through the [[Federal Interlocutor for M<U+00E9>tis and Non-Status Indians]].  Aboriginal political organisations throughout Canada vary in political standing, viewpoints, and reasons for forming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/aboriginal-heritage/020016-4010-e.html|title=Post-war Rise of Political Organizations|work=Library and Archives Canada| accessdate = 2009-10-06}}</ref> First Nations, M<U+00E9>tis and Inuit negotiate with the [[Politics of Canada|Canadian Government]] through [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]] in all affairs concerning land, entitlement, and rights.<ref name="price"/>  The First Nation groups that operate independently do not belong to these groups.<ref name="price"/>

==Culture==
:''Further information: [[:Category:Aboriginal culture in Canada|Aboriginal culture in Canada]] and [[Aboriginal Canadian personalities]]''
[[Image:Snow Shoe Maker between ca. 1900-1930.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt="Black and white photo of a woman kneeling on the ground making a snowshoe. She is wearing a plaid shirt and white dress locking down at the snowshoe. Around her is four frames of snowshoe to be made leaning on a tippy, |Traditional [[snowshoe]] maker, c. 1900.]]
Countless North American Indigenous words, inventions and games have become an everyday part of [[Spoken languages of Canada|Canadian language]] and use. The [[canoe]], [[snowshoe]]s, the [[toboggan]], [[lacrosse]], [[tug of war]], [[maple syrup]] and [[tobacco]] are just a few of the products, inventions and games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edu.gov.mb.ca/k12/cur/socstud/foundation_gr2/blms/2-2-1c.pdf |format=PDF |title=Diverse Peoples <U+2013> Aboriginal Contributions and Inventions|work=The Government of Manitoba| accessdate =2009-10-17 }}</ref> Some of the words include the [[barbecue]], [[Reindeer|caribou]], [[chipmunk]], [[Groundhog|woodchuck]], [[hammock]], [[skunk]], [[mahogany]], [[Tropical cyclone|hurricane]] and [[moose]].<ref name=Edinburgh>{{cite web |last=Newhouse|first=David|url=http://www.cst.ed.ac.uk/2005conference/papers/Newhouse_paper.pdf |format=PDF |title=Hidden in Plain Sight Aboriginal Contributions to Canada and Canadian Identity Creating a new Indian Problem|work=Centre of Canadian Studies, University of Edinburgh| accessdate =2009-10-17 }}</ref> Many North American and South American areas, towns, cities and rivers have [[List of place names in Canada of aboriginal origin|names of Indigenous origin]]. The word "Canada" derives from the [[Laurentian language|St. Lawrence Iroquoian]] word meaning "village" or "settlement".<ref>{{cite book|first=Bruce G. Trigger |last=James F. Pendergast |year=1978|title= Saint-Lawrence Iroquoians |work=Handbook of North American Indians. Volume 15. |publisher=Smithsonian Institution |pages= 357<U+2013>361|isbn=0773500700}}</ref> The province of [[Saskatchewan]] derives its name from the [[Saskatchewan River]]; which in the [[Cree language]] is called "Kisiskatchewani Sipi", meaning "swift-flowing river."<ref name=places/> Canada's capital city [[Ottawa]] comes from the [[Algonquin language]] term "adawe" meaning  "to trade."<ref name=places>{{cite web |url=http://www.ainc-inac.gc.ca/ai/mr/is/info106-eng.asp |title=Aboriginal place names contribute to a rich tapestry |work=Indian and Northern Affairs Canada| accessdate =2009-10-17 }}</ref> Modern youth groups such as  [[Scouts Canada]] and the [[Girl Guides of Canada]] include programs based largely on Indigenous lore, arts and crafts, character building and outdoor camp craft and living.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/scoutsource/CubScouts/AboutCubScouts/history.aspx |title=History of Cub Scouting |work=Boy Scouts of America| accessdate =2009-10-17 }}</ref>

Aboriginal cultural areas depend upon their ancestors' primary [[Types of societies|lifeway]], or occupation, at the time of European contact. These culture areas correspond closely with [[geography of Canada|physical and ecological]] [[List of regions of Canada|regions of Canada]].<ref name="three">{{cite book
|editor=Goddard, Ives
|others=W. C. Sturtevant
|title=Languages. Handbook of North American Indians
|volume=17
|year=1996
|publisher= Smithsonian Institution
|location=[[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D. C.]]
|isbn=0-16-048774-9.
}}</ref> The [[indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast]] were centred around ocean and river fishing; in the interior of British Columbia, hunter-gatherer and river fishing. In both of these areas the salmon was of chief importance. For the people of the plains, bison hunting was the primary activity. In the [[taiga|subarctic forest]], other species such as the [[moose]] were more important. For peoples near the Great Lakes and [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Shifting cultivation|shifting agriculture]] was practised, including the raising of [[maize]], [[bean]]s, and [[Squash (plant)|squash]].<ref name="three" /> While for the Inuit, hunting was the primary source of food with [[Pinniped|seals]] the primary component of their diet.<ref name="Searles">{{cite book
|last=Searles
|first=Edmund
|title=Food & Foodways: History & Culture of Human Nourishment
|year=2002
|pages=55<U+2013>78
|chapter=Food and the Making of Modern Inuit Identities. Volume 10, Number 1, 1 January 2002
|isbn=0806121262
|quote=Although the Inuit of the Canadian Arctic have access to an ever-expanding market of different kinds of foods, they continue to invest considerable time and money obtaining Inuit foods, that is, foods hunted, fished, and gathered within the Inuit homeland.
}}
</ref> The [[Reindeer|caribou]], fish, other [[marine mammal]]s and to a lesser extent plants, berries and seaweed are part of the [[Inuit diet]]. One of the most noticeable symbols of [[Inuit culture]], the [[inukshuk]] is the emblem of the [[Vancouver]] [[2010 Winter Olympics]]. ''Inuksuit'' are rock sculptures made by stacking stones; in the shape of a human figure, they are called ''inunnguaq''.<ref name=vancouver>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancouver2010.com/ |title=Vancouver 2010 Olympic Games Emblem |work=2010 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games| accessdate =2009-10-17 }}</ref>
[[Image:Tsuu Tsina parade.JPG|thumb|alt="Colour photograph of Tsuu T'ina children in traditional costume on horseback at a Stampede Parade in front of an audience"|[[Tsuu T'ina Nation|Tsuu T'ina]] children at a parade]]
[[Indian reserve]]s, established in [[Law of Canada|Canadian law]] by treaties such as [[Treaty 7]], are lands of First Nations recognised by non-indigenous governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://74.125.93.132/search?q=cache%3ALX5RxMzdkJsJ%3Awww.uarctic.org%2Fmodule_12_tmDGm.pdf.file+Land+Claims%2C+Ownership%2C+and+Co-management&hl=en&gl=ca|title=Land Claims, Ownership, and Co-management|work=Developed by Ken Coates, Dean, College of Arts and Sciences, University of Saskatchewan and Greg Poelzer, Chair, Political Science Program, [[University of Northern British Columbia]]|format=PDF|accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> Some reserves are within cities, such as the Opawikoscikan Reserve in [[Prince Albert, Saskatchewan]], [[Wendake, Quebec|Wendake]] in [[Quebec City]] or [[Stony Plain 135, Alberta|Stony Plain 135]] in the [[Edmonton Capital Region]]. There are more [[List of Indian reserves in Canada|reserves in Canada]] than there are First Nations, which were ceded multiple reserves by treaty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.literacycommunity.com/grade3/firstnations/reserve.htm|title=The First Nations-Communities: Reserves|work=The Literacy Community| accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> Aboriginal people currently work in a variety of occupations and may live outside their ancestral homes. The traditional cultures of their ancestors, shaped by nature, still exert a strong influence on them, from spirituality to political attitudes.<ref name="three" />  National Aboriginal Day is a day of recognition of the cultures and contributions of the First Nations, Inuit and M<U+00E9>tis  peoples of Canada.  The day was first celebrated in 1996, after it was proclaimed that year, by then [[Governor General of Canada]] [[Rom<U+00E9>o LeBlanc]], to be celebrated on June 21 annually.<ref name=history>{{cite web |url=http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/R32-179-2000E.pdf|title=National Aboriginal Day History|work=Indian and Northern Affairs Canada |format=PDF  | accessdate = 2009-10-18}}</ref> Most provincial jurisdictions do not recognise it as a [[Public holidays in Canada|statutory holiday]].<ref name=history/>

===Languages===
:''Main articles: [[Spoken languages of Canada#Aboriginal languages|Aboriginal languages]], [[Inuit language]] and  [[Canadian Aboriginal syllabics]] ''
{{See also|Eskimo<U+2013>Aleut languages|Indigenous languages of the Americas}}
There are 11 [[Spoken languages of Canada#Aboriginal languages|Aboriginal language groups]]  in Canada, made up of more than 65 distinct dialects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/tbt/Rp-eng.cfm?LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=89149&PRID=0&PTYPE=88971,97154&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=733&Temporal=2006&THEME=73&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=|title=Aboriginal languages|work=Statistics Canada|accessdate = 2009-10-05}}</ref> Of these, only [[Cree language|Cree]], [[Inuit language|Inuktitut]] and [[Ojibwe language|Ojibway]] have a large enough population of fluent speakers to be considered viable to survive in the long term.<ref name="online">{{Cite book
  | last = Gordon
  | first = Raymond G Jr.
  | title = Ethnologue: Languages of the world
  | place = Dallas, Texas
  | publisher = SIL International
  | year = 2005
  | edition = 15
|format=Web Version online by SIL International,formerly known as the Summer Institute of Linguistics
  | url = http://www.ethnologue.com/web.asp
  | isbn =1-55671-159-X
  | accessdate = 2009-10-06
  | postscript = .
}}
</ref> Two of Canada's territories give official status to native languages. In Nunavut, Inuktitut and [[Inuinnaqtun]] are official languages alongside the national languages of English and French, and Inuktitut is a common vehicular language in territorial government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.langcom.nu.ca/languages/en_index.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080405002637/http://langcom.nu.ca/languages/en_index.html|archivedate=2008-04-05|work=Office of the Languages Commissioner of Nunavut|title=Nunavut's Languages | accessdate =2009-10-02 }}</ref> In the NWT, the ''Official Languages Act'' declares that there are eleven different languages: [[Dene Suline language|Chipewyan]], Cree, English, French, [[Gwich<U+2019>in language|Gwich<U+2019>in]], Inuinnaqtun, [[Inuktitut]], [[Inuvialuktun]], [[Slavey language|North Slavey]], [[Slavey language|South Slavey]] and [[Dogrib language|T<U+0142><U+012F>ch<U+01EB>]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Official Languages Act
  | work =  Legislation
Division, Department of Justice
  | year = 1988
  | url = http://www.justice.gov.nt.ca/PDF/ACTS/Official_Languages.pdf
  | format =PDF
  | accessdate =2009-10-02 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080625231116/http://www.justice.gov.nt.ca/PDF/ACTS/Official_Languages.pdf |archivedate = June 25, 2008}}
</ref> Besides English and French, these languages are not vehicular in government; official status entitles citizens to receive services in them on request and to deal with the government in them.<ref name="online" />

